name: PLA
description: PLA is super easy to print, cheap, and available in many colors. It's the stiffest non-composite thermoplastic and has excellent tensile strength.
pros: Easy to print, cheap, stiff, excellent tensile strength.
cons: Susceptible to UV light, shatters when dropped, can't be sanded or glued well.

name: Silk PLA
description: Silk PLA has a special additive that makes your prints shiny. It's more metallic than actual metal but weakens the print.
pros: Shiny, easier to remove supports, aesthetically pleasing.
cons: Weakens the print, can puff up during printing.

name: Carbon Fiber PLA
description: Carbon Fiber PLA sharpens details, stabilizes the filament as it cools, and makes the end product stiffer but more brittle.
pros: Sharpens details, stabilizes cooling, crisp details, low shrinkage, matte finish.
cons: More brittle, requires a hardened steel nozzle.

name: Metal-Filled PLA
description: Metal-filled PLA contains metal shavings that make prints heavier and adds some properties like patina and magnetism.
pros: Heavier, develops patina, magnetic (if iron-filled).
cons: Extremely brittle, expensive, weak.

name: Wood PLA
description: Wood PLA is plastic mixed with sawdust. The quality varies, and it feels like hardwood when finished.
pros: Feels like hardwood, convincing wood grain effect with varnish.
cons: Weaker, absorbs humidity, difficult to print.

name: Tough PLA
description: Tough PLA is a combination of PLA and polybutene terephthalate (PBT). It resists higher temperatures and handles impacts better.
pros: Higher temperature resistance, impact-resistant, doesn't shatter.
cons: Higher cost than regular PLA, may require slight adjustments in print settings.

name: Matte PLA
description: Matte PLA contains plant pulp, giving prints a springy satin surface. It can be sanded, painted, and carved.
pros: Springy satin surface, can be sanded, painted, and carved.
cons: Absorbs humidity quickly, semi-flexible, can jam in the extruder.

name: High-Speed PLA
description: High-Speed PLA melts at a lower temperature and has reduced viscosity, allowing for faster printing speeds.
pros: Allows for high-speed printing, reduces print time significantly.
cons: Softens at lower temperatures, can be problematic in hot climates.

name: Flex PLA (PCL)
description: Flex PLA (PCL) is a low-temperature printing filament with a waxy consistency, useful for prosthetics and sculptable plastics.
pros: Low-temperature printing, can be reshaped with warm water, useful for prosthetics.
cons: Translucent waxy consistency, no adhesive sticks to it.

name: PETG
description: PETG is tougher than PLA, handles higher temperatures, and is more transparent. It has a low coefficient of friction.
pros: Tough, handles higher temperatures, transparent, low friction.
cons: Poor overhang performance, absorbs water quickly.

name: Carbon Fiber PETG
description: Carbon Fiber PETG combines PETG with carbon fibers, resulting in a stiffer material with less warping and shrinkage.
pros: High stiffness, less warping, matte finish, improved dimensional stability.
cons: Requires a hardened steel nozzle, more brittle than regular PETG.

name: PCTG
description: PCTG is similar to PETG but offers increased impact resistance and clarity, with easier printing at lower temperatures.
pros: Increased impact resistance, transparent, easy to print.
cons: Slightly more expensive than PETG, limited availability.

name: PET
description: PET is known for its strength and durability, commonly used in food-safe applications and recyclable products.
pros: Strong, durable, food-safe, recyclable.
cons: Can be tricky to print due to warping, requires high temperatures.

name: CF PET
description: Carbon Fiber PET offers added rigidity and dimensional stability, making it ideal for applications needing high strength.
pros: Increased stiffness, high dimensional stability, minimal warping.
cons: More brittle, requires a hardened nozzle.

name: PVB
description: PVB (Polyvinyl Butyral) is known for its transparency and ability to be smoothed with isopropyl alcohol, making it ideal for clear, glossy prints.
pros: Clear finish, smoothable with alcohol, good layer adhesion.
cons: Low heat resistance, sensitive to humidity, not very strong.

name: ABS
description: ABS is tough and withstands high temperatures. It can be solvent-welded and vapor-smoothed with acetone.
pros: Tough, withstands high temperatures, can be solvent-welded and vapor-smoothed.
cons: Warps significantly, off-gases during printing.

name: ASA
description: ASA (Acrylonitrile Styrene Acrylate) is UV-resistant and weatherproof, making it ideal for outdoor applications.
pros: UV-resistant, weatherproof, strong layer adhesion.
cons: Requires a heated bed, prone to warping, emits fumes.

name: HIPS
description: HIPS (High Impact Polystyrene) is commonly used as a dissolvable support material and has good impact resistance.
pros: Soluble in limonene, impact-resistant, good for support structures.
cons: Limited strength, requires high temperatures, soluble only in specific solvents.

name: PA-6 Nylon
description: PA-6 Nylon is known for its exceptional strength and flexibility, ideal for functional parts under stress.
pros: High strength, flexible, good durability.
cons: Highly hygroscopic, requires a heated bed and enclosure.

name: PA-12 Nylon
description: PA-12 Nylon offers high impact resistance and low moisture absorption, making it stable in a variety of environments.
pros: Low moisture absorption, high impact resistance, good dimensional stability.
cons: Requires high printing temperatures, may need an enclosed build area.

name: PA-6 CF Nylon
description: PA-6 CF Nylon combines nylon with carbon fibers, offering enhanced stiffness, strength, and reduced warping.
pros: High stiffness, low warping, excellent strength-to-weight ratio.
cons: Requires a hardened nozzle, hygroscopic, needs high print temperatures.

name: PA-12 CF Nylon
description: PA-12 CF Nylon combines PA-12 Nylon with carbon fibers, providing excellent dimensional stability, low moisture absorption, and high stiffness.
pros: High stiffness, low moisture absorption, excellent dimensional stability, reduced warping.
cons: Requires a hardened nozzle, more brittle than standard PA-12, high printing temperature required.

name: Glass-Filled Nylon
description: Glass-Filled Nylon is reinforced with glass fibers, providing increased rigidity, dimensional stability, and strength, ideal for heavy-duty applications.
pros: High rigidity, excellent dimensional stability, strong and durable.
cons: Requires a hardened nozzle, high printing temperature, brittle compared to pure nylon.

name: Nylon/PETG Alloys
description: Nylon/PETG alloys combine the flexibility and strength of nylon with the easier printability and layer adhesion of PETG, resulting in a durable yet user-friendly material.
pros: High flexibility and impact resistance, good adhesion, easier to print than pure nylon.
cons: Lower heat resistance than pure nylon, moderate hygroscopicity, may still require a heated bed.

name: Polycarbonate (PC)
description: Polycarbonate is a highly durable material known for its impact resistance, transparency, and heat resistance, ideal for demanding applications.
pros: High impact resistance, heat resistant, strong and durable.
cons: Requires high printing temperatures, prone to warping, sensitive to moisture.

name: CF Polycarbonate
description: CF Polycarbonate combines polycarbonate with carbon fibers, offering enhanced rigidity, heat resistance, and dimensional stability.
pros: High rigidity, excellent heat resistance, low warping, strong and durable.
cons: Requires a hardened nozzle, high printing temperatures, more brittle than pure polycarbonate.

name: PMMA (Acrylic)
description: PMMA, or acrylic, is known for its transparency and hardness, often used for lightweight, clear parts.
pros: Transparent, lightweight, scratch-resistant, durable.
cons: Prone to warping, brittle, sensitive to moisture, requires controlled print environment.

name: PC-PBT
description: PC-PBT is a blend of polycarbonate (PC) and polybutylene terephthalate (PBT), offering improved impact resistance, flexibility, and chemical resistance.
pros: High impact resistance, chemical resistance, good flexibility, dimensional stability.
cons: Requires high printing temperatures, sensitive to moisture, can be tricky to print.

name: Chocolate
description: Chocolate can be used as a 3D printing material for food-safe applications, allowing for unique edible designs.
pros: Edible, food-safe, unique aesthetic possibilities.
cons: Requires specialized food printer, sensitive to temperature fluctuations.

name: TPU
description: TPU (Thermoplastic Polyurethane) is a flexible, rubber-like material, commonly used for applications requiring elasticity.
pros: Flexible, durable, impact-resistant, suitable for wearable parts.
cons: Difficult to print due to flexibility, requires slow print speeds.

name: TPE
description: TPE (Thermoplastic Elastomer) is a highly flexible material, ideal for producing parts with rubber-like elasticity.
pros: Very flexible, rubber-like properties, good durability.
cons: Challenging to print, prone to stringing and warping.

name: SEBS
description: SEBS (Styrene-Ethylene-Butylene-Styrene) is a flexible material with excellent UV resistance, suitable for outdoor applications.
pros: UV-resistant, flexible, suitable for outdoor use.
cons: Limited heat resistance, requires specialized handling for optimal print results.

name: Polypropylene (PP)
description: Polypropylene is a lightweight, flexible material with good chemical resistance, commonly used in household items.
pros: Lightweight, flexible, chemical-resistant, good fatigue resistance.
cons: Prone to warping, difficult to adhere to the bed, requires a heated bed.

name: Glass-Filled Polypropylene
description: Glass-Filled Polypropylene combines PP with glass fibers for added strength, rigidity, and heat resistance.
pros: High rigidity, improved heat resistance, strong and lightweight.
cons: Requires a heated bed, more brittle than pure PP, requires hardened nozzle.

name: OBC (Olefin Block Copolymers)
description: OBC is a flexible, impact-resistant material similar to polyethylene, used for applications requiring elasticity and durability.
pros: Good flexibility, impact-resistant, lightweight.
cons: Low heat resistance, challenging to print, adhesion issues.

name: HDPE (High-Density Polyethylene)
description: HDPE is a strong, chemical-resistant material often used in containers and piping.
pros: Chemical-resistant, strong, lightweight.
cons: Prone to warping, poor bed adhesion, requires a heated bed.

name: POM (Polyoxymethylene)
description: POM, also known as Delrin or acetal, is a strong, low-friction material ideal for mechanical parts like gears and bearings.
pros: High strength, low friction, good dimensional stability.
cons: Difficult to print, warps easily, requires heated enclosure.

name: PVDF (Polyvinylidene Fluoride)
description: PVDF is a durable, chemical-resistant material often used in chemical processing environments.
pros: Chemical-resistant, durable, good thermal stability.
cons: Difficult to print, requires high temperatures, sensitive to warping.

name: PEEK (Polyether Ether Ketone)
description: PEEK is a high-performance engineering thermoplastic with exceptional heat and chemical resistance, suitable for demanding industrial applications.
pros: Exceptional heat resistance, chemical resistance, high strength.
cons: Expensive, very high printing temperature required, requires heated enclosure.

name: PEKK (Polyether Ketone Ketone)
description: PEKK is similar to PEEK but offers improved printability and is ideal for high-strength, high-heat applications.
pros: High strength, excellent thermal resistance, better printability than PEEK.
cons: Expensive, high printing temperature required, sensitive to moisture.

name: PPS (Polyphenylene Sulfide)
description: PPS is a high-performance plastic with strong chemical resistance and thermal stability, used in demanding environments.
pros: Excellent chemical resistance, high heat tolerance, dimensional stability.
cons: Requires high print temperature, brittle, sensitive to moisture.

name: PSU (Polysulfone)
description: Polysulfone is known for its high-temperature stability and resistance to chemicals, ideal for applications in medical and automotive fields.
pros: High heat resistance, good chemical resistance, stable.
cons: High printing temperature required, sensitive to moisture, limited flexibility.

name: PES (Polyether Sulfone) and PPSU (Polyphenylsulfone)
description: PES and PPSU are high-performance thermoplastics with excellent chemical and heat resistance, often used in aerospace and medical applications.
pros: Exceptional chemical resistance, high heat tolerance, strong and durable.
cons: Difficult to print, high temperature required, sensitive to moisture.

name: Ultem 1010
description: Ultem 1010 is a PEI-based material known for its exceptional thermal stability and strength, suitable for high-performance industrial applications.
pros: High strength, excellent heat resistance, biocompatible.
cons: Very high printing temperature, requires specialized equipment, expensive.

name: TPI (Thermoplastic Polyimide)
description: TPI is an extremely high-performance polymer with outstanding thermal and chemical resistance, often used in aerospace and high-stress environments.
pros: Exceptional thermal stability, chemical resistance, suitable for extreme conditions.
cons: Extremely high printing temperature, very expensive, specialized equipment needed.
